We are positive on the Macau gaming industry in general, as monthly GGR remains above \(10\%\) YoY. We expect 2H GGR to be \(+15\%\) YoY. We expect Wynn Macau to gain share in 3Q (after losing share in 1H25). We also believe that its dividend (US \(250m\) annually) is the highest (in terms of yield at \(6\%\) ) in Macau. This should help the stock to trade at a higher multiple. Historically high dividend yield resulted in higher multiple.
We break down the results into three key areas - revenue, costs and earnings:

1) Revenue: Macau's 2Q25 GGR rose \(8\%\) YoY, reflecting an acceleration in industry growth. However, growth was driven by VIP (up \(24\%\) YOY), while mass revenue grew by only \(6\%\) YOY. More interestingly, VIP rolling chip volume only grew by \(8\%\) , suggesting the 2Q GGR uptick was mainly driven by the VIP win rate, which may normalize soon (Exhibit 3). In that case, GGR growth could normalize or mass growth accelerate. So far in 3Q, we see two months tracking around \(+15\%\) YOY, boding well.

2) Costs: Generally costs should rise at around 4-5% YOY since the majority of costs is labor. However, we see 2Q apex rising 13% YoY (Exhibit 5), reflecting the impact of expansion initiatives and non-gaming apex (mandated by government). At the same time, mass reinvestment ratios moved higher across the industry, signalling intensified competition. In addition, Sands China might step up reinvestment for underperforming properties, suggesting that competitive intensity may persist in the near term. This is the main reason why 2Q did not see margin expansion despite strong mass and GGR growth.
Exhibit 5: Daily operating expenditure
Source: Company data, Morgan Stanley Research.

3) Earnings: Despite industry EBITDA margin not rising, market share winners saw big EBITDA growth. MGM China, Melco and Galaxy outperformed peers, with growth largely supported by stronger market share gains. By contrast, Sands posted weaker hold-adjusted growth despite its higher mass contribution, reflecting both an elevated reinvestment rate and a sharp 22% decline in VIP rolling volume.
Meanwhile, Wynn Macau and SJM recorded negative earnings growth, primarily due to mass market share losses during the quarter.

Mainland package tour visitors (proxy for base mass) to Macau fell \(26\%\) YoY in July, continuing the downward trajectory seen throughout the year. This divergence versus the double- digit GGR growth underscores the dominance of day- trippers over overnight visitors, contributing to lower per- capita spending.

Report - Hong Kong Macro Strategy, Economics, Property and Banks: Is the HIBOR Spike a Headwind? (20 Aug 2025)
We refresh our interest rate sensitivity analysis to gauge the effects on spiking HIBOR with latest reported figures from results.

Earnings of Henderson and NWD are the two names most vulnerable to HIBOR spike, with relative large balance of debt. Average 1m- HIBOR stayed at \(2.56\%\) in 1H25 and property companies could incur higher finance costs in 2H if HIBOR remains elevated at \(3\%\) or above in the rest of the year.

But interestingly, Sino Land could leverage higher HIBOR to earn interest income given net cash position (Jun- 25 HK\\$49.5bn). Wharf could also be immune from this impact as virtually all debt is RMB- denominated at relative low cost.
Despite effective mortgage rate returned to the cap rate of \(3.5\%\) , we believe that prime rate movement (with US Fed rate) is more important for long- term sustainability of lower mortgage rates.
Our US economics team now expects FOMC to cut the funds rate by 25bp in September and follow with quarterly cuts of 25bp to a terminal of \(2.75 - 3.0\%\) by end- 2026 (see full report here).

We remain constructive on the residential market as imminent rate cut could continue to drive property price/volume higher, as we suggested previously that home price could have stabilized already in June.

Report - Sino Land: FY25 EPS - 5%, DPS Flat, 100% payout (27 Aug 2025)
Sino Land (EW) reported F2025 results on August 27.

- F2025 EPS was down 5% YoY, but it kept DPS flat (6.3% yield), and confirmed it is possible to maintain considering huge cash pile (net cash is \(\sim 60\%\) of market cap). However, payout has already reached 100%, and interest cuts could hurt its interest income.

- The company is optimistic on recovery of the Hong Kong property market, showcased by recent land acquisition of a Tuen Mun site at a premium showcased its confidence. The company will continue to take part in upcoming land tenders.

- One Central Place, a residential project located at Central with 121 units in total, has been changed for leasing due to robust demand from talent and foreigners. So far, more than 20 units have leased since July. Management is pleased for the strong demand and pretty rentals of HK\$100+/sqf.

- Management also noted in the briefing that Conrad Hong Kong is planned to undergo renovation to increase product quality and competitiveness. Occupancy of Conrad increased 5ppt to 74% in F2024-25, but average room rate was under pressure.

**SHKP (OW)** will report 2025 results on September 4.

·We expect underlying profit in 2025 to grow slightly, 1% YoY, to HK$5bn, supported by strong contracted sales from Sierra Seas and NOVO LAND Phase 3A in 1H25, and stable recurring income base from rentals. But DP margin could be under pressure (F1H25/F2H24 25%/15%), on impairment provision.
·Full-year DPS could stay flat YoY at HK$3.75, at 49% payout on underlying profit.
·Key focus on the results include: 1) upcoming launch pipeline (HK DP and China IP) in 2026; 2) DP and IP margin trends; 3) property market outlook; and 4) investment appetite.

·We expect the upcoming launch of Cullinan Sky Phase 2 at Kai Tak could achieve high sell-through (90%+) with good market response, as it did for Phase 1, where 897 units (~98%) were sold. Land cost of the project is at HK$17.8k/sqf.

RevPAR recent trend: Some investors were excited about 3Q25 RevPAR decline being narrower than 1H25. However, we believe this cannot be extrapolated into 4Q25 or next year as 3Q25 is dominated by leisure demand and the narrower decline only shows leisure is more resilient than business demand (which is known to the market). We still expect 4Q25's decline to widen back to \(- 4\%\) level seen in 2Q25. HTTH did not give 4Q25 RevPAR guidance but management pointed out that there will be only one October Golden Week holiday in 4Q25, so it is not comparable to 3Q25. See Exhibit 18.

Franchisee confidence: Both companies mentioned industry supply growth faster than expected is a fact. It is not clear when supply growth can subside to mid- or low- single- digit growth, but both companies will be more selective in hotel openings. HTTH believes the peak in franchisees' interest in adding a hotel has passed. Another trend is top hotel brands are taking even more market share in new openings.

\((\pmb {+})\) EOP REIT (Ow): Interest cut tailwinds and high exposure to the Bangalore market (strong leasing, rent growth and lowest vacancy) and GCC \((62\%)\) of gross rental). Total return of \(\sim 16\%\) with F2026e DPU growth of \(10\%\) YoY and yield of \(6\%\) is strong and excludes acquisitions.

\((\pmb {+})\) Prestige (Ow): Strong presales momentum with F2026 growth expected to be \(50\%\) YoY/Rs260bn (F1Q26 was \(300\%\) YoY), strongest amongst peers. Management guidance of Rs250- 270bn backed by Rs299bn launch pipeline and Rs207bn inventory. Implied multiples based on F2026 presales look inexpensive with P/E at 15.3x and EV/EBITDA at 9.5x vs. averages of \(17.4x\) and \(11.7x\) , respectively.
India property stocks were \(- 4\%\) WoW, while Sensex was \(- 2\%\) WoW.

(- ) 3Q25 (July) launches declined (LTM \(- 2\%\) QoQ) for the first time in five years on monsoon seasonality, but momentum should rebound with festive demand. Mumbai, Bangalore were strong and NCR/Hyderabad weak.
\(+\) Sales strengthened, up \(6\%\) LTM QoQ, led by strong demand in Bangalore and Mumbai.
\(= )\) Top 6 cities, saw \(5\%\) YoY price growth moderating from \(8 - 11\%\) last two quarter. NCR led with \(19\%\) YoY growth, followed by Mumbai and Bangalore at \(7\%\) YoY.
\(+\) Unsold inventory eased to 16 months, lowest in Gurgaon (7) and highest in Hyderabad (25 vs. 26 last quarter).

We remain OW on Prestige on strong F2026 momentum \((+50\%)\) YoY vs. \(- 19\%\) in F2024), supported by Mumbai, Bangalore exposure. Lodha (EW on expensive valuation) benefits from Mumbai's stability, while Oberoi, DLF and Godrej remain launch- driven and may face a soft September quarter.
